USA
[1] Michigan, Livingston County warning
Date: Tue 18 Apr 2017 1:55 p.m. ET
Source: Detroit Free Press [edited]
http://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2017/04/18/livingston-measles-brighton-restaurant/100606832/


Livingston County Health Department officials are warning [residents] they may have been exposed to measles.

The warning follows a confirmed case of measles in a Livingston County resident. It affects anyone who was at [specific locations listed in URL above]. "This is not a matter of food safety or restaurant sanitation," Chelsea Moxlow, health promotion coordinator said in a press release [Mon 17 Apr 2017]. "The individual with measles was a customer of the restaurant while contagious."

"Both facilities are working with LCHD to help notify employees and members of the public about the potential exposure to measles," she added.

Measles is "highly infectious disease," Livingston County Medical Director Dr Don Lawrenchuk said. "You don't even have to be in the same room with someone to get the infection," he said. "There have been cases where someone sick with measles was in a doctor waiting room and someone sat in the same waiting room that was never vaccinated and came down with the disease by breathing the same air from 2 hours before."

The Livingston County resident was exposed to the measles while traveling on the same airplane as an unrelated child who was not vaccinated and returning from a country where many measles cases were reported. Health officials did not say which country.

Anyone who was at the restaurants or the Brighton hospital during the given times is asked to monitor themselves for 21 days - or until [Tue 25 Apr2017] - for rash with fever or other symptoms consistent with measles, which is a highly-contagious, airborne disease.
The illness starts with a runny nose, red eyes, cough, fever and sore throat and tiny white spots may appear in the mouth. A raised, red rash appears on the 3rd - 5th day of illness and it typically starts on the face and spreads down the body.

Health officials said having 2 doses of the measles, mumps and rubella, or MMR, vaccine at least 28 days apart is "fully protective." Having one dose of MMR vaccine is about 93 percent protective.

The 1st dose is routinely given to children after their 1st birthday. Vaccination is not necessary if an individual has a prior history of measles illness.

[Byline: Lisa Roose-Church]

