******
Asia
[5] India, Uttar Pradesh
Date: Thu 20 Apr 2017 01:07 IST
Source: Business Standard [edited]
http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/3-children-die-of-measles-in-up-village-117042000042_1.html


Measles claimed the lives of 3 children in Nairainpur Bhatan village under Kerakat district Uttar Pradesh. northern India

Cases of measles have been reported from the village and additional medical teams have been rushed there, CMO Ravindra Kumar said.

There were some cases of measles and the locals were getting treatment from nearby doctors but 3 children ages 3,3, and 1 died one after the other, the CMO said.

Up to 4 others aged between 2 and 5 years were being treated at the Kerakat Community Health Center and all necessary precautions were being taken, he said.

A vaccine-preventable disease, measles is caused by a virus from the paramyxovirus family and spreads through air and direct contact. It is a highly contagious airborne infection.

India accounts for over one-3rd of the world's 134 000 measles annual deaths, shows World Health Organization (WHO) data.

Measles deaths declined by 51 percent from an estimated 100 000 in the year 2000 to 49 000 in 2015, according to the WHO.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[On the WHO website reviewed March 2017, it also states 134 000 deaths annually from measles as does the report above (mostly children under 5; about 367 deaths every day or 15 deaths every hour) (http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs286/en/). However, the WHO website states that deaths have declined by 79 percent from year 2000 to 2015 from an estimated 651 600 in 2000 to 134 200 in 2015 due to vaccination. It is likely the report above got 51 percent reduction in deaths to 49 000 from an earlier model run by WHO. In 2015, about 85 percent of the world's children received one dose of measles vaccine by their 1st birthday through routine health services - up from 73 percent in 2000. During 2000-2015, measles vaccination prevented an estimated 20.3 million deaths making measles vaccine one of the best buys in public health. - Mod.LK]

